Project 3: Phishing Simulation and Email Spoofing Awareness Research

Objective

The objective of this project was to study phishing attack methodologies through authorized simulations and understand both attacker techniques and defensive email security controls used to protect organizations.

Project Description

In this project, I conducted phishing awareness simulations using cloned login portals and spoofed email concepts to understand how attackers use deception to harvest credentials. Using SocialFish and Medusa Phisher, I created phishing scenarios that replicated trusted organizational login pages.

I studied phishing techniques involving lookalike domains, deceptive URLs, trusted branding abuse, and social engineering methods used to manipulate users into submitting credentials.

The project also explored email spoofing awareness, including the study of phishing indicators such as suspicious sender behavior, domain impersonation, and trust abuse techniques. I researched how attackers attempt to make malicious communications appear legitimate.

Alongside offensive simulation, I focused on defensive security mechanisms including SPF, DKIM, DMARC, secure email gateway protections, anti-phishing awareness strategies, and detection methods used by security teams to identify phishing attempts.

This project improved my understanding of both phishing attack infrastructure and the controls organizations use to reduce phishing risk.


